        <section class="section">
            <h2>Basic Rules</h2>
            <p>Chess is a two-player strategy board game played on an 8x8 grid called a chessboard. The game is played with 16 pieces per player, each with specific movements.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Pawns move forward one square, capture diagonally.</li>
                <li>Rooks move horizontally or vertically any number of squares.</li>
                <li>Knights move in an "L" shape: two squares in one direction and then one square perpendicular.</li>
                <li>Bishops move diagonally any number of squares.</li>
                <li>Queens can move horizontally, vertically, or diagonally any number of squares.</li>
                <li>Kings move one square in any direction.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The objective is to checkmate the opponent's king, which means the king is in a position to be captured (in check) and cannot escape.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Chess Pieces</h2>
            <p>Each player starts with:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>8 Pawns</li>
                <li>2 Rooks</li>
                <li>2 Knights</li>
                <li>2 Bishops</li>
                <li>1 Queen</li>
                <li>1 King</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Pieces are placed on the board in a specific arrangement at the start of the game.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Strategy and Tactics</h2>
            <p>Chess involves strategic planning and tactical maneuvers to control the board and gain advantage over the opponent. Key strategies include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Controlling the center of the board.</li>
                <li>Developing pieces efficiently.</li>
                <li>Creating pawn structures to support your position.</li>
                <li>Executing effective attacks and defenses.</li>
                <li>Understanding common tactical motifs such as forks, pins, and skewers.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Studying famous games and practicing regularly are essential to improving your chess skills.</p>
        </section>

        <div class="cta">
